**Errors are indistinguishable from valid output**: Every tool handler returns `format!("error: {e}")` on failure. MCP tool results are plain strings, and the caller (an LLM or editor) has no structured way to distinguish an error from a successful result that happens to start with "error:". The MCP protocol has a proper error-reporting mechanism (`CallToolResult::error`/`is_error` flag); these should use it. As-is, an LLM client might interpret a failure as successful data and hallucinate based on the error text.